\section{Introduction}
This module aims to give students an introduction to the working of financial markets.  It also seeks to provide the opportunity for students to develop, apply and test theories and tools that have learnt throughout the course.  It aims to integrate economics, finance and accounting skills in the development of investment strategies.  It will provide an introduction to R and statistical programming.  The module will be divided into three main sections: case studies that involve the simulation of  financial market activities;  the collection, analysis and presentation of economic and financial data; the application of financial techniques to develop trading strategies. 

\section{Assignments} 
The module will help you to develop the investment tools that you have been taught.  This will culminate in a presentation of an investment idea on Friday $15^{th}$ April 2016.  Three assignments will guide you towards this presentation.  The tasks are an assessment of hedge fund performance, an event study and a technical trading strategy.  The three tasks will covered on $20^{th}$ November 2015, $15^{th}$ January 2016 and $4^{th}$ March 2016.  There is an assignment that will test you knowledge of market-mechanisms and microstructure. This will be handed in on $22^{nd}$ April. There is a clear link between the quality of the final presentation and the participation in the class.   The presentation counts for 40\% of the final mark for the module and the four other assignments contribute 60\%.  Though the presentation it will come at the end of the year, you should start thinking about it from the beginning of the module. You should think about the areas of the course that have been of most interest to you and how you could apply them to an investment task.

