\section{Journal Articles}
In addition to this, there are a number of journal articles that will be very useful for you.  I will add to the list of journal articles as we progress. In some parts of these articles, there will be a lot of mathematics that will be difficult.  However, the basic ideas are usually presented in the first few pages.  It is extremely useful to get use to reading journal articles and it will improve your overall level of understanding of the type of analysis that will be required across your course. 
\par
\vspace{5 mm}
W. F. M. De Bondt \& R. Thaler (1985). `Does the Stock Market Overreact?'. \emph{The Journal of Finance} 40(3):793-805.
\par
\vspace{5 mm}
E. F. Fama (1998). `Market efficiency, long-term returns, and behavioural finance'. \emph{Journal of Financial Economics} 49(3):283-306.
\par
\vspace{5 mm}
B. G. Malkiel (2003). 'The Efficient Market Hypothesis and its Critics, \emph{The Journal of Economic Perspectives} 17(1): 59-82
\par
\vspace{5 mm}
R. J. Shiller (2003). 'From Efficient Markets Theory to Behavioural Finance, \emph{The Journal of Economic Perspectives} (17)1: 83-104
\par
\vspace{5 mm}
You should be able to find these in the on-line library.  There is a tab on student central that will take you to the library.  You should use the database to search.  A very good database to start with for older papers is JSTOR (you will find Malkiel and Shiller there); you will find De Bondt and Thaler in the Business Source Premier database; you will find Fama in Science Direct.
There are links to the articles in student central. 

